 @ARTICLE{deursen2022,
   title    = "Increasing incidence of reported scabies infestations in the
               Netherlands, 2011-2021",
   author   = "van Deursen, Babette and Hooiveld, Mari{\"e}tte and Marks, Susan
               and Snijdewind, Ingrid and van den Kerkhof, Hans and Wintermans,
               Bas and Bom, Ben and Schimmer, Barbara and Fanoy, Ewout",
   abstract = "INTRODUCTION: Several Public Health Services and general
               practitioners in the Netherlands observed an increase in scabies
               in the Netherlands. Since individual cases of scabies are not
               notifiable in the Netherlands, the epidemiological situation is
               mostly unknown. To investigate the scabies incidence in the
               Netherlands, we described the epidemiology of scabies between
               2011 and 2021. METHODS: Two national data sources were analysed
               descriptively. One data source obtained incidence data of scabies
               (per 1,000 persons) of persons consulting in primary care from
               2011-2020. The other data source captured the number of
               prescribed scabicides in the Netherlands from 2011-2021. To
               describe the correlation between the incidence of diagnoses and
               the number of dispensations between 2011 and 2020, we calculated
               a correlation coefficient. RESULTS: The incidence of reported
               scabies has increased by more than threefold the last decade
               (2011-2020), mainly affecting adolescents and (young) adults.
               This was also clearly reflected in the fivefold increase in
               dispensations of scabicide medication during 2011-2021. The
               incidence and dispensations were at an all-time high in 2021. We
               found a strong correlation between the reported incidence and the
               number of dispensations between 2011 and 2020. CONCLUSIONS: More
               awareness on early diagnosis, proper treatment and treatment of
               close contacts is needed.",
   journal  = "PLoS One",
   volume   =  17,
   number   =  6,
   pages    = "e0268865",
   month    =  jun,
   year     =  2022,
   language = "en"
