              forward the resulting parameter uncertainty in a Bayesian
              framework to consider the economic cost of delayed interventions
              against scabies, quantifying the benefits of prompt action in the
              event of detection. We also revisit the previous methodology used
              to assess the safety of treatments in small population
              sub-units-in this context ivermectin-and demonstrate that even a
              very slight relaxation of the implicit assumption of homogeneous
              death rates significantly increases the plausibility of the
              hypothesis that ivermectin does not cause excess mortality based
              upon the data of Barkwell and Shields.",
  journal  = "PLoS Comput. Biol.",
  volume   =  14,
  number   =  3,
  pages    = "e1006046",
  month    =  mar,
  year     =  2018,
  language = "en"
}



